    aiSummary: 'User retention for AI features is notoriously low. The cause is usually the "Novelty Trap"—users try the feature because it\'s cool, but stop because it doesn\'t solve a recurring pain point or requires too much prompting effort. Stickiness comes from "Invisible AI" that works in the background without user intervention.',
    content: 'We\'ve all seen the "AI magic" demo that fails to translate into daily usage. Product data shows that 70% of AI-powered features are abandoned within 30 days. The reason? They require too much cognitive load. If a user has to think about a prompt, the friction is too high. The features with the highest retention are "Invisible AI"—features that anticipate user needs and execute automatically. Think of Cursor\'s "Tab" to complete or Gmail\'s smart categories. They don\'t feel like "AI"; they feel like the product is just smarter. To build sticky AI, founders must move from "AI as a tool" (user-initiated) to "AI as an agent" (system-initiated). The goal should be reducing the number of clicks and thoughts required to achieve an outcome.',
    founderTakeaway: 'Audit your AI features: do they require a prompt? If yes, try to eliminate it. Use context from the user\'s current state to predict what they need. Retention lives in the clicks you eliminate, not the prompts you enable.',
    imageUrl: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1551288049-bebda4e38f71?w=800&q=80',
